  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 23:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἄνδρα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἄνθρωπον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": Bengel and Wendt take the word to indicate a certain degree of respect.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "συλλ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: used in various senses, but in all four Gospels of the capture of Jesus, and in Luke, where the word is frequent, often of the capture of prisoners, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 1:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 12:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 26:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:54",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Plummer) so in LXX.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μέλλοντα ἀναι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: “was about to be killed,” R.V.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπιστὰς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": the word seems to intimate that he was ready at the right moment to rescue the prisoner.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τῷ στρατ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: “with the soldiers,” R.V., those under his command.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐξειλόμην",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 7:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "μαθὼν ὅτι Ῥ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: “qua ratione id compererit, tacere satius erat,” Blass. The chiliarch wishes to put the best interpretation on his own conduct after his hastiness in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 21:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 22:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see reading in [375] text. Overbeck and Wendt (and even Zöckler) defend the chiliarch from a crafty misrepresentation, and compare the condensed explanation of the letter and the facts given in the narrative to the different accounts of Saul’s conversion, but the chiliarch had a motive for dissembling his real part in the transaction, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "viz.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", fear of punishment.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[375] R(omana), in Blass, a first rough copy of St. Luke.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "This man was taken of the Jews",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The verb implies a seizure or arrest. It is used (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 14:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of the party of men who came to seize our Lord, and (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 12:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of Herod Agrippa’s arrest of St Peter.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "It is to be noted that the chief captain employs the word for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "man",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which in the original implies respect, no doubt because he was presently about to mention that he was a Roman citizen. The same distinction exists in Latin as in Greek, so that the original may have been in either language. There can be little doubt that Roman officers at this time were familiar enough with Greek to write in it, if need were.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and should have been killed of them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Rev. Ver.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " modifies the obsolescent English, and reads “was about to be slain of them.” The chief captain does not give a very exact report of what had happened. He says nothing about the strife between the two religious parties; perhaps he did not understand its nature and cause.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "then came I with an army, and rescued him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Rev. Ver.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when I came upon them with the soldiers, and",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.” This must refer rather to the first rescue from the mob in the Temple-precincts (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 21:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). There is no word said of what happened afterwards, the binding with two chains, and the intention of scourging the prisoner.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "having understood",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "R. V.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "learned",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "that he was a Roman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The chief captain put this in such wise as to claim credit for interference on behalf of a Roman citizen, and in so doing omits to state that it was only when Paul was about to be scourged and protested against it, that he was discovered to be a citizen of Rome by birth.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
